title: Grateful Dead Live at Radio City Music Hall on 1980-10-29
description:
Set 1

Dire Wolf, On The Road Again, It Must Have Been The Roses, The Race is On, Bird Song, Heaven Help The Fool, Ain't No Lie-> Ripple

Set 2

Feel Like A Stranger-> Franklin's Tower, Me & My Uncle-> Big River, Candyman-> Little Red Rooster, Tennessee Jed, Looks Like Rain, Althea-> The Music Never Stopped

Set 3

China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider-> Estimated Prophet-> Terrapin Station-> Drums-> The Wheel-> Saint Of Circumstance-> Black Peter-> Sugar Magnolia, E: U.S. Blues

First Set Acoustic

reviews.review_text:
Building for the zenith
One of the 3-set Fall '80 shows shot by Showtime and slated for the special, though little was used. The show isn't as big as the final two nights, but the highlights are different, with a terrific 3rd set sequence. First Set. An average acoustic set of 3SF80 - until the end. The vid cuts in during Must've Been Roses. The exchange following, with Ramrod being teased by Bobby, after passing him tea, is only on some sources ("I can't fucking believe it" laughs Jer). After a wobbly Race Is On, Jer calls Bobby's mistake a "change in the arrangement". The great tuning has Bobby playing Spring Song (instead of Jer). After Bird Song Bobby suggests The Frozen Logger, but instead Phil & Mickey step offstage for Heaven Help the Fool. Ripple was played for all 25 3SF80 shows, but this is one of the top few. Even if not the best of the acoustic sets overall, they had the most fun. Second Set. Stranger is decent, and Franklin's is hot throughout 3SF80. The rest of the set is mostly average '80. Candyman is the familiar album cut; not spectacular but smooth - and unedited, one of just two such tracks on the original Dead Set. But that release did chop up the following Little Red Rooster. The 3 edits shorten the intro (4sec cut @0:14 & 22sec cut @0:19) and cut a verse + a great solo from Brent + Bobby's Slide Practice™ + Jer's 2nd solo (5:28 cut @3:26). Jer teases Peggy O, then calls for Sugaree, but then agrees to Tennesee Jed [this tuning is cut on some sources]. The last three are AUD (the Jim Wise is best) on all but the vid source. Music Never Stopped is an uptick spark to leave 'em happy for the break. Nothing wrong with these sets, but 3SF80 was so strong that not all stand out from the rest of the pack. Third Set. This wonderful China Cat sends the excitement to the highest levels, all the way through a doric Rider. Phil is great on a perfect Estimated, and by Terrapin they have entered that magical place where it just comes easy and the Heads are all tethered in the stratosphere. When they leave the stage for Drums, Billy does a full stop so he can put on his shoe (explaining to Mickey and the film crew). The following multi-cam vid is some of the best-ever footage of Rim Debils. Both drummers stay out for Space. The Wheel is part draggy, part cool, but tight overall, with a nice drop into Saint. The seg into Black Peter is also nice, those it's a very rote version (likewise the Sugar Mag). The U.S. Blues leaves 'em happy because Brent and Bobby still have some juice. 1st Set:  C+ 2nd Set: C 3rd Set:  B- Overall = 3 stars Highlights: Ripple - live-woodshedded to this point China Cat Sunflower - starts a whopping sequence I Know You Rider - excitement is high level Estimated Prophet - Bobby good, Phil so good Terrapin Station - magical/tethered SOURCES: Most sources have pitch errors and hiss (including 140301_sbd-partial_miller_sirmick). The best source is the 140899_sbd_aud composite. It updates the tetzeli_join-1953-32538 and is the most complete, with the first and second sets re-pitched. However, the 3rd set has had the digital speed monkeyed with (it streams at the right pitch, but at a sped tempo). Use the Tetzeli, the vid, or the gatto-jaeger_dusborne for the third set. The latter is the most-balanced AUD in terms of freqs, separation, and low crowd chatter. The original vid is usually up on YouTube, and this source sounds better in some places. The existing footage starts at Must've Roses, is missing part of Race>Bird, and has a ½min cut in Saint. Selections from the show have been released three times. The Showtime special An Evening with the Grateful Dead has part of Must've Roses, plus Ripple & U.S. Blues. It used to circulate on VHS and is still around. Dead Set has Candyman and a heavily edited Little Red Rooster. The Scrapbook DVD has China Cat>Rider.
